		<td><b>Re: ados, an OS for NES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The BIOS provided a simple ABI for disk (13h), video (10h), keyboard (16h), BASIC (18h), RTC (1Ah), serial (14h), and parallel (17h) ports. DOS added some abstractions, including filesystem, memory management, and some other generic I/O (mostly 21h). Sometimes third-party software extended it with things like mouse (33h) or network drivers, or programs like DESQview which provided some degree of fault tolerance and preemptive multitasking.<br /><br />The balance between &quot;when do things belong in your libc&quot; or &quot;when do things belong in your OS&quot; has some wiggle room.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

